<p style="text-align:justify;">all manner of happiness in the course of its life, and that it may live to wear gray hairs and see its Grand Children: &#8211; if the Parson is an Old man, he wishes the child to look at the Sun at least as long as he did, and then sings a song again, in which he names the child &#8211; the whole of the feast must be eaten up, and sometimes lasts several hours which the guests employ in eating and smoking, and the Parson in singing and beating the drum.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">I was invited to several of their feasts on different occasions, and was always obliged to get help to finish my share, which was far above my appetite, especially as I never did relish these feasts; as the Indians are the dirtiest cooks on earth, and filthiest gluttons; for an Indian can eat as much as he pleases.</p>
